english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent in Farewell to the Duke Zhao, Inspector-General of the Northwest Region and Military Commander of Pyongyang
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the seventh spring of our sovereign's reign, as the court began to place greater importance on provincial appointments, Duke Zhao of Pingyuan received his commission and prepared to depart. The officials of the court, wishing to honor him, composed poems in his farewell, and entrusted me with writing this preface.

    I reflect that the Northwest Region serves as the nation's bulwark—connecting us above to the Middle Kingdom and defending us below against barbarian incursion. When the court appoints inspectors and magistrates to such a place, their selection must be made with utmost care. Only a person possessing both civil and military talents, whose authority and benevolence inspire universal respect, can adequately fulfill such a charge.

    Looking to the records of antiquity, this land was once the domain bestowed upon Kija, where the Nine Counsels of his teachings and the Eight Ordinances of his law took root deeply in the hearts of the people. Through more than a thousand years, this became the very wellspring of Eastern civilization. Yet in its later age, it fell to Wiman's seizure, until the Han Emperor dispatched forces to expel him and established a commandery. Subsequently, when the line of Chu-mong took dominion and made Pyongyang their capital, the ancient customs of Kija persisted still, and there followed more than six hundred years of peace. But as decline set in, So Mun grew wicked and brought upon us the armies of Sui and Tang. After So Mun's death, his two sons contended for power, and the nation fell with him. Later, the Wang dynasty's founder unified these lands, making repeated journeys to the Western Capital to suppress the restless. Yet from So Mun's time onward, those who harbored love of rebellion never ceased to arise—in the age of the Humane King came Yu Cham and Chong Shim; in the age of the High King came Ch'oe Kwangsoo and Cho Seung-yu; in the age of the Won King came Won Jin and Ch'oe Dal. All plotted treachery and raised rebellion, requiring military campaigns to suppress them. Even in the Wang dynasty's final decline, those appointed as inspectors and magistrates could not govern the southeastern regions as they should, resorting instead to mere temporary palliatives, causing all discerning minds to lament.

    But since the founding of our dynasty, we have regarded north and south equally, wielding both grace and authority in concert. What once could not be governed has now become governable. We have reformed the system whereby native leaders held military command, now having magistrates bear responsibility for militia training while the native people serve in support roles, with inspectors holding supreme authority. Thus the proper order of weightiness and lightness has been achieved, and the people rejoice as if released from hanging inverted.

    Yet customs remain not wholly refined, tax burdens not wholly equitable, wandering refugees not wholly settled, schools not wholly established, land boundaries not wholly rectified, and household registers not wholly clear. This rests upon whether inspectors and magistrates apply their hearts with complete sincerity. The Duke, blessed with clear character and lofty understanding, recognized early where Heaven's mandate was turning. From our sovereign's days as heir, he devoted himself, offering counsel and strategy, and became a luminous founder of our nation. Having served in offices both central and provincial with distinguished merit, and having aided in stabilizing the realm during perilous times, he has made the nation's security his personal charge. Now, receiving this new commission to govern a region, I am confident that the Duke will surely emanate his lord's virtue and authority, clarify instruction and transformation, preserve what has been well established while advancing what remains incomplete. He will labor to restore the legacy of Kija, cleansing away the corruptions of So Mun. Through moral cultivation and the fostering of propriety, he will ensure that in every household there dwells filial piety and respect for elders, and in every heart there lives loyalty to superiors and readiness to honor the great. Thus both military and civilian governance shall prosper.

    As for those moments of leisure—ascending the Floating Blue Tower to gaze upon the mountain vistas, or sailing upon the Great River composing verse in joyful inspiration—these are pleasures I would accompany if I could, yet cannot. Should he chance upon fine passages, I would be grateful were he to send them to ease the loneliness of parting in my declining years and to sustain the bond of our mutual regard.
  footnotes:
    - 'Kija (箕子): A legendary sage of ancient China who, according to tradition, fled to Korea and became a cultural founder, representing the transmission of Chinese civilization to the Korean peninsula.'
    - 'The Nine Counsels and Eight Ordinances: Principles of governance traditionally attributed to Kija.'
    - 'So Mun (蘇文, also Yeon Gaesomun): A 7th-century political figure whose rise led to conflicts with Tang China.'
    - 'Floating Blue Tower (浮碧樓): A famous pavilion in Pyongyang overlooking the Taedong River.'
    - 'Great River (大同): The Taedong River, which flows through Pyongyang.'
